The paper discusses the use of physical unclonable functions (PUFs) for secure key generation in resource-limited devices, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The focus on using SRAM in microcontroller units and batteryless computational RFID devices suggests a connection to embedded systems (cs.CY) and emerging technologies (cs.ET). The use of fuzzy extractors for turning noisy PUF responses into usable cryptographic keys relates to information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the development of a lightweight and secure PUF key generator for resource-limited devices involves machine learning and artificial intelligence techniques (cs.LG).
